’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The surname is still chiefly found in the regions around these villages.","English: nickname from Middle English<i>mannly</i> ‘manly, virile, brave’ (Old English<i>mannlīc</i>, originally ‘man-like’).","Irish (County Cork): Anglicized form of <b>Ó Máinle</b> (and often pronounced <i>Mauly</i>), of unexplained etymology. Compare   Malley  ."]},{"name":"O'Malley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Colm, Cormac, Brigid, Cahal, Colum, Conal, Conor, Delma, Donal, Eamon.","Irish (Mayo and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Máille</b>. This is of uncertain derivation. Woulfe suggests a Celtic source <i>maglios</i> ‘prince, champion, poet’. There is a Gaelic adjective <i>mall</i> ‘slow, stately’, and another, <i>málla</i>, meaning ‘sedate, pleasant’, and an abstract noun <i>máille</i> ‘stateliness’; the source could be any of these."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Malley was born about 1285, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mary. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1285–Deceased":"umbes 1285–Surnud","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1315–1375":"1315–1375","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1375":"1375","1285":"1285","Of, Malley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1285–Deceased":"noin 1285–Kuollut","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","1315–1375":"1315–1375","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","Abt 1285":"noin 1285","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1375":"1375","1285":"1285","Of, Malley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Englanti,